A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits into the dashboard of every car.
The devices that track every mile driven and report the information to the authorities are the focus of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state planning offices to revise the outdated system to finance U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the kilometers driven – and possibly also where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax rulings.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while there is no agreement in Congress on any action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently looking at how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re just likely to use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record miles driven by all California drivers in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, financed by the taxes paid by Americans at the dispensing pillar, is bankrupt.
But in America, it is not as much fueled as it used to be.
Cars consume less gasoline.
The state oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a penny at high fuel prices.
“The petrol tax is simply not sustainable,” says Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is popular with urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way that traffic jams and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
The California planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined climate change goals.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also inspired by the idea of having drivers pay for distances travelled.
“This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole,” explains Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move toward mile-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would include 10,000 cars.
However, the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move and responded to the concerns of MEPs from rural areas, who represent people who often have to travel many miles on the way to work or into the city in everyday life.
Several states and major cities, however, are moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which currently enlists 5,000 drivers for the nation’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently exploring how to implement the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, drivers were skeptical that the government could track any of their moves.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big deal,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and earnings management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
As the test began, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, cumbersome technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that the state can use to capture miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
This, according to Khan, would also make the public more reassured.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not run to help states tax drivers.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers should pay on the basis of miles driven.
But the devices tested by it are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more willing to get involved when their speed and locations aren’t recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
In some of these public pilot programs, major mistakes have been made.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose no device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Others hope to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a device for taxation that can also pay parking fees, only have to pay insurance for kilometers driven, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits that the system offers,” the city’s planning document states.
However, some traffic planners wonder if all the talk about paying per mile isn’t just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or an annual levy could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so they too pay a fair share.
“There is no reason for surgery if an aspirin is enough,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
