Esa decides on big space missions: missions for billions
Faraway planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the next few years.
Thirty proposals were available, five are still in the race.
distant worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there is life at least on some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origins of the cosmos?
Or hunting for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These questions are being asked by those responsible for the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their program "Cosmic Vision" they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are intended to decisively advance research.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were debated, five of which have now been narrowed down.
Numerous committees are reviewing the proposals, following up with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Program Committee.
A total of four major questions have been selected by the ESA to be answered by the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme launched in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets that circle these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to investigate this question, the Cheops Space Telescope is set to launch in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our surroundings will be investigated in more detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could image Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, looking for "biomarkers": gases that are considered to be an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately to reveal the prerequisites for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation emitted from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated as an example.
With the "Solar Orbiter" the Esa has already approved a mission of the M-Class (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is to launch in 2017 and closely monitor the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the Esa is the first of the three L-Missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer spacecraft is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and investigates the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons of Europe, Callisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
There may also be deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter common to us, consisting of stars, planets and living beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters together, and dark energy, through whose action the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy are.
With "Euclid" the ESA has already approved an M-mission, the launch of which is scheduled for 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time across the entire sky, thus allowing conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, the best chances of obtaining a permit as an L-Mission has "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission envisions a detector consisting of two or three probes, which will be stationed in space.
It could also detect gravitational waves that arose during the Big Bang, and thus provide new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes among others, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which is to be found on Earth, among others.
Suggestions have already been eliminated for, among other things, the transport of samples back from Mars, the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as solar physics.
