What happens on the way to my email?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Was the letter secret technically implemented in the design of the Internet service e-mail similar to that of the conventional post?
When designing early internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have not been careful to provide a stable foundation for a hearing-proof exchange of letters.
Therefore, a traditional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If the user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two connected directly?
In the first step, Anna’s email program or browser sends the email to the mail server of its service provider.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the way, the mail can run through a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Will traditional emails be read on their way through the web?
Most emails are read several times by software robots on the way.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do robots have another task?
In systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information that Google needs to place contextual advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google may display corresponding links to holiday deals.
Do unknown people read the emails?
The likelihood of unauthorized persons reading an email is extremely low.
In theory, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal opportunities to intercept or take notice of emails.
In addition, there are possible illegal surveillance activities.
Is it possible to protect emails from being read?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be encrypted effectively against reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to conceal the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that even who has communicated with whom cannot be easily recognized.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the e-mail market in Germany?
