George Kerevan: European unbundling gives the Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story of independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed-wire border along the Hadrian’s Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde template pointed to the potential economic benefits that would entail more freedom of travel in the rest of Europe, but it did not play a role – as expected – in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favorable to them.
Since Scotland is currently not part of the Schengen area, the continued non-compliance for Brussels would be just a small concession in return for what one really wants from the Scots.
So not really a story.
And one that has come in such a way in the years that it already resembles a fossil: The first time I heard the "independence means passport control" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance after the European pipe?
Why trade the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great plan for the unification of Europe, drawn up after the war, has come to a halt.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe officially died.
All over the EU, parties are gaining ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a Community currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – was able to win nearly five million votes in the Bundestag election in September, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in conjunction with the forced jacket into which the respective national economy is forced by sticking to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pinned its members to exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave it that way.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deepening European productivity problem.
As a result of the "green" energy directives issued by Brussels - a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much for electricity as the United States and four times as much for gas.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world’s wage bills do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is raging, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France’s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle that could keep Germany in check and raise Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, with which the struggling French economy has to struggle.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-opposing Front National has just won a decisive by-election, thus pointing the ruling socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a right-wing split would automatically bring benefits to the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among working-class white French?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the last analysis) small-England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can do.
I suspect that Scotland could do quite well in a looser European alliance, if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and keeping our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – notably – the most successful political movement against austerity policies in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition had to blame.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to get an austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts Believe Epidemic Obesity Is a Trigger of Early Puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics’ annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are relatively normal among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually that’s not an indication that puberty is fast coming,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious indications of development, such as growing breasts, sham and axle hair, as well as body odor, show up in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (the appearance of the first menstrual bleeding) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
“When the development of the breasts begins, it takes at least two to three years until the menarche,” said Kaplowitz, also author of the book “Early puberty in girls: The essential guide to dealing with this frequently occurring problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually represents the onset of puberty, but it is considered “early” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt aged eight years.
In most cases, the process slows or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progression, tests by an endocrinologist could be indicated so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and defending against another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the child’s age, developmental speed, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reluctant when it comes to medication, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings of being unlike their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They're worried about the risk of pregnancy or about how they handle the hygienic side," Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her days at the age of ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home frightened and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys come into puberty similar to girls before.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported conducting a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine, linking body fat to entry into puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty more than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and puberty hair grows earlier, the trend towards full earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference stressed the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and sham hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually reacts well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
