New Anti-Nicotine Vaccine Could Shut Down Smoking Pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
More trials are needed before testing in humans, which can take a few more years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are good.
“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to quit trying all the methods available on the market but had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain genetic information about the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies chase the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, causing a smoker to not experience nicotine high.
In trials, vaccinated mice administered nicotine maintained their normal activity levels.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, took a “break,” the researchers said, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is quite certain, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
But more likely, smokers would use it to quit.
“Then you know, when you start smoking again, you don’t feel any pleasure about it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps you get rid of the habit,” he explains.
