Regulations on electronic devices on aircraft remain in force in Australia
Australian air passengers must continue to turn off tablets and smartphones at take-off and landing, despite efforts in the US to loosen regulations for such devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allows U.S. airlines to change their specifications so that passengers on their devices can read, watch, or play e-books during critical flight phases, provided they are in “flight mode.”
Passengers are already allowed to do this during most of the flight, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian companies are observing the decision that U.S. airlines will have to do a lot of work to implement, but are not pursuing direct plans to change their regulations.
The air traffic control agency CASA also said it would look at the announcement, but stressed that the restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases in Australia still apply.
“Currently, CASA does not have any specific regulations regarding the use of electronic devices in the aircraft,” it said.
The topic is subject to provisions that require airlines to maintain safety at all times and that passengers follow the safety instructions given by cabin crew.
Virgin has already held talks with CASA about expanding its Wi-Fi entertainment system on flights, saying it is open to changes, but they need to be initiated by lawmakers.
“We would welcome a review of CASA’s approval of electronic devices because we are convinced that this would improve the customer experience after we now offer (wireless entertainment) during the flight,” a spokesperson said.
Qantas said it will stay with the current regulations until further notice.
“Our current policies provide that electronic devices may not be used during take-off and landing, and we currently have no plans to change that,” the company said in a statement.
The FAA rules apply to U.S. airlines.
However, we are always interested in developments in regulations that can benefit passengers, and we will certainly look closely at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it.
The decision affects US companies differently depending on the age of the fleet.
They must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from mobile devices, and modify manuals, training materials, hand luggage programs, and customer instruction.
“After an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any height,” the FAA said in a statement.
In rare cases with poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off the equipment during landing.
The group also recommended storing heavier equipment safely under the seat or in the compartments above the seats during take-off and landing.
