Pawnshops boom in Singapore as crisis has arrived in middle class
In a pawnshop in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay for her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, and all my money is in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) a month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia — where household debt is increasing — is so great that ValueMax, where it traded, this week became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
Placing jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, Singapore pawnshops demand an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent demanded by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping mall.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that there is no need for credit checks or income proofs, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
This is why millions of people in the region are turning to pawnshops after families feel the pressure of rising living costs and rising household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to loose financial policies in developed economies, lower- and middle-income families are looking for pawnshops to make up for the difference in the tumbling economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor’s described growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product, according to the agency.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continued weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have further intensified the trend of pledging personal items as people seize the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city state’s 200 pawnshops are gold.
People are saying, "The gold price looks good, let's pledge Grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
The largest Thai pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent customer growth in its branches in recent months.
The growth in the lien business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is financing this with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it took this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have fallen into the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only bid lower interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase debt.
“Customers lend items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables does not increase budgetary training,” she explains.
The leasing business is increasingly accepted as a short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use liens are in financial trouble.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax stores to pawn gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from all social strata come to us.
“This includes wealthy people who are short-term lending for a business or investment, or small businesses that need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
