325 Million Australian Dollars Rescue Package for Tasmanian Healthcare
The Australian government insists on the harsh conditions associated with the $325 million Australian health care bailout package to ensure that the state government cannot waste the money.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek has announced that the Commonwealth will take “immediate action” to avert a crisis caused by an aging population of the island state, a higher rate of chronic diseases and system constraints.
The four-year funding was decided after government consultations with independent Tasmanian MP Andrew Wilkie.
“The government has put together an emergency rescue package that we believe addresses the unique challenges facing the state,” Mr. Plibersek said today.
The $325 million package includes $31 million in emergency election assistance.
A further 2,600 surgeries, including orthopedic procedures and treatments for grey star, will eliminate residues.
In addition, there is money for day clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better aftercare for inpatient stays, specialist training, mental health services and the introduction of a system for electronic recording of health data in local hospitals.
“These investments are in line with the ideas that affected clinic staff told me were the best way to improve the Tasmanian health system,” said Tanya Plibersek.
The minister insisted on a strict reporting and accountability obligation of the Tasmanian government.
The state must maintain the current level of funding to receive money from the Commonwealth and report monthly on where the additional funds were spent.
A three-member commission is set up to ensure that the state provides health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie explained today, the $325 million would be of little use if “it is not accompanied by real reforms that will put the public Tasmanian health system on a more sustainable course.”
Nevertheless, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent help, which he first expressed to the prime minister in early May.
“I am confident that federal aid will make a major contribution to removing the state’s public health system from the list of concerns,” Wilkie said.
According to the state government, these election services will largely compensate for the recent cuts.
But the opposition’s health policy spokesman at the federal level, Peter Dutton, is of the view that today’s announcement is just a “plaster solution.”
“We are in today’s situation because the lab state government has withdrawn $430 million from the health care system,” he told ABC TV.
It cannot be that a state government pulls almost half a billion dollars out of the system and puts 300 million into the Commonwealth and then pretends to be the good news.
Dutton called on Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the bailout package would be spent on additional bureaucracy.
