Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, according to a monitoring group
Syria has destroyed key chemical weapons and GVG facilities, the global chemical weapons watchdog said Thursday, as clashes broke out in the north of the country near one of the sites where suspected toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the start of the civil war almost three years ago.
The announcement of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came one day before the date on
On 1 November, the Hague-based organization had set up Damascus to destroy or render “inoperable” all facilities for the production of chemical weapons, including all machinery for mixing chemicals into poison gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is basically the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all of Syria’s chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus still has to start destroying the existing weapons and supplies.
According to estimates, there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday, where experts say there is a production facility for chemical weapons and deposits, the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
The group, which tracks the death toll through a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29,954 of them belonged to the army of President Bashar Assad, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 were Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the number of deaths in this conflict since March 2011 to be 100,000.
This number has not been updated so far.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad’s troops have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels, many of whom have ties to al-Qaeda groups.
The observatory said there were losses on both sides on Thursday, but gave no details.
The fighting underscores the danger to which the chemical weapons inspectors are exposed, as their mission to liberate Syria from its poisonous arsenal of weapons is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team is “now convinced that it has seen all the important production and mixing/filling facilities mentioned by Syria and witnessed their destruction.”
Therefore, "there are currently no further inspection activities planned."
Earlier this week, the inspectors said they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 out of 23 of the sites indicated by Damascus.
Due to security concerns, it was not possible to visit two facilities, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPWC said the two sites had been abandoned, according to Syrian statement, "and the chemical weapons program objects there had been relocated to other named facilities that were inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has submitted a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
“I take the hat off of the bravery and courage that you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization,” said Ahmed Uzumcu, the director-general of the monitoring organization, in a commentary published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting this civil war against Assad’s government and its security forces, many of which are members of the Alawites, a secession of Shiite Islam.
Rami Abdurrahman, the head of the monitoring group, said Wednesday there was a heavy explosion at an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is not known, he said.
