FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but not make phone calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music, and watch movies from flight to land, but not phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depended on the respective airline, FAA staffer Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight personnel training manuals as well as the regulations for the storage of the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
You may not start it again until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing, passengers must turn it off again and must not start it again before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even during take-off, landing and on the rolling field, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been retrofitted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented securely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit,” Glading said.
We are honestly tired of having to feel like a watchman on this issue.
Nevertheless, internet connections for browsing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data below three kilometers remained prohibited, the agency explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still not “Words With Friends,” the Scrabble-like online game actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he publicly had to leave an American Airlines jet for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops still need to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight are also prohibited.
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) is the regulator of telephone calls, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission poles,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a broader use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to ease restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri believe there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is mentioned that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore turning off the device.
In 1966, the FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers after reports of disruption of navigation and communication devices by passenger-carrying FM radios became known, which at that time represented the latest technology trend.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA in such a way that they do not care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years when the flight altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suited for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when flipping.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Advocates of easing restrictions on passenger use include Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to identify problems, but could not detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the device disruption is genuine, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there were only occasional reports of pilots talking about disruption of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended the FAA to allow pilots to order the shutdown of the devices by the passengers in the event of a landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable fit for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a comfortable passenger experience does not conflict with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
