Is Europe’s elite ready to do business with the UK?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing the economy to a table and defining what those who provide prosperity and work in the UK want to change our relations with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey among UK business leaders and asked them what they think about the UK, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business executives, roughly representing UK company sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies are now exporting outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing while countries in the EU are stagnating.
They want the government to favor new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than stopping the long and strenuous process of reforming the obscure EU institutions.
Asked about certain legal issues – from antitrust to product legislation – the majority of business leaders believe that control over these key competencies should be brought back to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction over the single market, as the companies said the costs of Brussels regulations would now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe’s trading zone – even 40 percent of large companies agreed with the one that has traditionally been the most Europe-friendly.
Finally, and that probably says most, our survey of business leaders found that a clear majority wanted Britain to take a course towards changing the agreement and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This finding, found among companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that the economy is pushing for a “meaningful change” that brings the issue of action back to the UK.
It’s about a lot – a change to the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a 16 percent change of mind in favor of staying in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should have no doubt: this survey shows that the British economy stands behind his plan to renegotiate the British conditions for EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a significant shift in power relations back to the UK from a renegotiation.
A better deal for the British economy is possible and increasingly necessary as the eurozone moves towards closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the result of our survey shows, what means for companies a greater focus on trade and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to regulations.
