Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA employees charged on charges against Jonathan Lord for sex offenses
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) were charged with child-related sex offenses before charges were filed against child caregiver Jonathan Lord of Caringbah in 2011, according to the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse.
But in the opening statement before the Commission, the YMCA stated that “the organization has never had to deal with an incident of child sexual abuse.”
Managing Director Phillip Hare was questioned about a case in which one YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offenses, and another in which a YMCA Caringbah Hall sports teacher was convicted in 1991 of abuse of children entrusted to him.
Hare said Gail Furness, one of the commission’s assistant attorneys, knew about the first case, but didn’t know about the second one.
