Scientists were able to shed more light on the relationship between a dog’s tail swollen and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with their tails swung more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and react to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right brains respond differently to stimuli that elicit positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just as in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail swings of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films from other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the cock moves in one direction, in the other direction
Professor Vallortigara said, “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to use it to steer the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved its tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the whirling dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tilt was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog waving), their heart rate increased and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs had learned from experience what movements they should worry about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the waving with the tail is linked in a direction rather to friendly behavior and the right side rather produces a less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers to better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right is important for dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a satisfied dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, it was stated: “Dogs are more likely to go to a robotic dog when its ‘tail’ wiggles to the left and not to the right, rather than to become restless – exactly the opposite of the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
"While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined - and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
But since their behavior is simply recorded, it will probably not take long for us to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
