In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a spokesman for the Vatican, said there would be a meeting of all cardinals before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as the Consistory, would be held.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the Consistory in February in advance so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be planned,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of eligible cardinals is likely to decline by February.
He explained that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as necessary so that the number of eligible cardinals will again be 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wishes.
The Consistory next year is important because it is the first since Francis’ election in March this year, Valero said.
There is currently a certain overhang in Europe and in particular in Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The cardinals will also be the first to be appointed since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from all over the world who are tasked with finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything alone.
“Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He declared that it was “well possible” that Francis would ask the cardinals for advice.
