Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewerage channel from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
Those who visit Cologne do not pass the cathedral.
Around 157 meters, the two towers protrude into the sky and make it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who marvel at the two filigree church towers, know that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert on Cologne’s underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacular: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too large remained of the remains of the old city wall.
Most users of the car park therefore today also rush past the Roman remains and only leave their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal lattices on the parking deck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins of hand plate-sized stones.
"There are remnants of the Roman city wall built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze says.
Before going back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants take a look at a dark 15-metre-deep shaft on the upper level of the park.
This is the fountain of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants climb down again into the depths.
Here we see the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Praetor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means as much as "City of Roman law and city of the Agrippinians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the praetorium is the former governor’s palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the anteroom of the exhibition, a tunnel leads to the Roman sewage channel, which is preserved here on about 120 meters in length.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After picking up the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep in the ground to get to the groundwater, which was indispensable for the ritual washings.
To this day, at the lower end of the Mikva, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which construction work is to begin shortly.
However, it will take a few more years to complete.
