In an unprecedented admission, John Kerry said US spying went “inappropriately far.”
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, hinted at a softening of the U.S.’s defensive stance on its surveillance programs, saying the espionage had “got too far in some cases.”
The foreign minister also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, was responsible for switching to “autopilot” when whistleblower Edward Snowden’s explosive revelations about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
Through the leaked information, the US government has fallen into a diplomatic storm of indignation on the part of its allies.
